 on comparison with Europe. Archer challenges these explanations by comparing the United States with its most similar New World counterpart--Australia. This comparison is particularly revealing, not only because the United States and Australia share many fundamental historical, political, and social characteristics, but also because Australian unions established a labor party in the late nineteenth century, just when American unions, against a common backdrop of industrial defeat and depression, came closest to doing something similar. Archer examines each of the factors that could help explain the American outcome, and his systematic comparison yields unexpected conclusions. He argues that prosperity, democracy, liberalism, and racial hostility often promoted the very changes they are said to have obstructed. And he shows that it was not these characteristics that left the United States without a labor party, but, rather, the powerful impact of repression, religion, and political sectarianism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLabor unionsxPolitical activityzAustraliaxHistory. 0aLabor unionsxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPolitical sociology. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400837540zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400837540423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400837540.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL